text.tspan: Integrated Wealth Management
Bank of America
-'Erica' is the firm's AI-based personal assistant for clients to use on its banking app
- Using AI, virtual reality and the metaverse as part of an immersive training program for its 2,000 new hires (started in 2023), which helps cut costs and improve performance

-In July 2025, the CTO and CIO stated, “AI is having a transformative effect on employee efficiency and operational excellence,” and that, “Our use of AI at scale and around the world enables us to further enhance our capabilities, improve
employee productivity and client service, and drive business growth.”
More detail in the 'Case Study' section
BNY
- Built predicitive ML tool to help clients avoid settlement failure in clearance of the ~$10TR/day in the US Treasury market, for which BNY acts as the sole provider of clearance services.
- Uses Microsoft's AI-driven 'Copilot' tool to increase efficiencies for both advisors and programmers; see developers as 25% more productive using this tool
- Incorporates AI in its new Pershing X WOVE platfrom to deliver personalized, efficient experience for advisors
- Set up a R&D hub in Dublin, Ireland to drive innovation in AI and machine learning
- BNY became the first major bank to deploy Nvidia's DGX SuperPOD, which will accelerate our processing capacity to innovate, reduce risk and launch AI-enabled capabilities.
- Expects AI-related expense benefits to play out over the medium-term (i.e. 2026 and beyond)
- OpenAI Partnership (February 2025): BNY announced a multiyear agreement with OpenAI to enhance their proprietary enterprise
AI platform, Eliza, and scale AI-powered solutions across global operations. This partnership provides the bank with access to
OpenAI's API and ChatGPT Enterprise platforms, as well as expert insights.
- Carnegie Mellon University Collaboration (September 2025): BNY entered a five-year, $10 million agreement with Carnegie Mellon
University to support world-class research and development in artificial intelligence, known as "BNY AI Lab"
- Employee Adoption: 97% of employees on AI platform Eliza (as of Sept 25).
- Personal AI Agents: 13k employees created their own AI agents (as of June 25).
- Digital Employees: 66 introducing "digital employees" into the BNY workforce (as of June 25).
- AI Activities in Production: Approx. 100 (as of Sept 25).
Citi

- CEO commented on LinkedIn in July '23 that generative AI would drastically improve productvity in the near-term; "It has the potential to revolutionise all functions across our bank and the industry — changing how we write code, onboard
clients, service customers, detect fraud, develop market research and strengthen compliance and controls." Such initiatives have been in flight for at least three years.
- Stated that the firm is modernizing its infrastructure and data security through AI, leading to fewer operating losses
- 'We're learning from best practices and we're using some great AI and other data tools that are helping to identify anomalies in data and data flows much quickly.'

- In December 2024, Citigroup launched new AI tools for approximately 140k employees across eight countries to "simplify work and increase productivity." Two primary tools were introduced: 1) Citi Assist (searches internal policies and
procedures), and 2) Citi Stylus (summarizes, compares, or searches multiple documents).

-In the 1Q25 earnings call, Citi announced the introduction of Agent Assist, their first generative AI tool for customer service in U.S. Personal Banking, designed to help service teams resolve inquiries faster (initially piloted in credit cards)
- In the 2Q25 earnings presentation, Citi highlighted its expanded the adoption of Gen AI tools with the rollout of new features

that enable faster and easier access and increasing overall productivity. Additionally, Citi cited the firm is live in production with Agentic AI for development work, putting Citi at the forefront of AI-driven engineering.
- Scaled usage of two enterprise tools in first half of 2025, including a ~5x sequential increase in 2Q
- ~740K automated code reviews completed in our Gen AI developer tool, saving ~100K hours per week across our developer
population

- In July 2025, Citi partnered with Ant International to pilot the Ant International's AI-backed Falcon Time-Series Transformer model, helping aviation clients improve the accuracy of cash flow and FX exposure forecasts, and reduce costs.
Goldman Sachs

- Per the CIO, the firm has 'a lot of proof of concepts ongoing. Nothing is at the production stage.' An example is document classification and categorization that would speed up due diligence across many functions. Others include

summarizing earnings calls and other research. For AI use in coding, the CIO has seen in some cases up to 40% of AI-written code being accepted by the developer - but that this tech is moving fast and could take months rather than years to
reach production. Constraints include a need to create appropriate control frameworks, talent, and hardware availability.
- Led an investment round in H2O.ai in 2019

- 'I think we don't know the extent to which AI can impact the total picture. It's definitely very, very interesting. We're spending a lot of time on it. We're also focused, frankly, on governing the way in which it's rolled out, users, the datasets, et

cetera. So, as it grows, as we learn and explore different ways to apply it, both defensively and offensively in our opinion, doing so in a very controlled, well-governed manner is also very important given the overall nascency of this
technology.'

-'Double-clicking and getting more narrowly focused on Goldman Sachs, I would just say we see enormous opportunities for productivity gains and also opportunities for efficiency. Our use cases that we're testing and that we're implementing

focus on those two areas. But I'd really like the focus to be more on productivity and the ability to scale our smartest people to do more with our clients, rather than expecting an efficiency gain that becomes very cost accretive.'

- In January 2025, GS released a program called GS AI Assistant to ~10K employees; By June 2025, the firm announced the broader rollout of GS AI Assistant across the company to raise productivity. The firm described it as "the first

generative AI-powered tool to reach this scale, allowing for safe, secure and responsible access to firm approved external large language models." This initially mostly produced answers based on company data fed into AI models from
OpenAI's ChatGPT, Google's Gemini, and Meta's Llama, with GS also looking at mdoels from Anthropic, Mistral, Cohere and other companies.

- GS has emphasized a "two-pronged approach" - scaling their internal GS AI platform while utilizing strategic partnerships with external providers to access "the best external capabilities and the latest, most impressive models."

- In July 2025, GS announced a significant partnership with Cognition Labs to pilot Devin, an autonomous generative AI agent designed for software development; CEO Solomon has said, "It did something in an hour that would take 10
engineers a few days." (Sept'25).
- In Sept. 2025, the CEO also noted GS has "very detailed plans on a variety of areas" where they believe they can make progress in "reimagining processes, creating automation, creating efficiency."
JPMorgan
- Planning to invest $1Bn annually on AI/analytics;
Now have spent ~$2Bn, with $2Bn in benefits so far (as of June 2025).
- Developing a ChatGPT-like AI software called IndexGPT
- Firm is using AI to detect fraud, training/surveillance, and enhancing KYC processes,
among >450 other use cases - including 100 GenAI solutions in production.

- "I think that operational efficiencies, in my view, it will be the biggest impact over the short to medium-term rather than any of the other use cases that you have probably heard about it." (Sept '24)

"While we've made substantial progress over the last decade, we are still in the early stages of our AI journey. We are focused on modernizing data, investing in scalable platforms and being at the forefront of innovation as technology
evolves, positioning the company for sustained future success." (May'25)
- More detail in the 'Case Study' section
Northern Trust
- In the 'experimentation phase' right now; highlighted potential efficiencies related to documentation; noted the focus from compliance and regulators on building guardrails around using AI
- Developing a virtual assistant to help Wealth Advisors manage relationships
- Leveraging AI for compliance/AML and portfolio management
- Started leveraging Saphyre's patened AI technology to streamline operational support for pre-trade through post-trade processes, aimed at its Investment Operations clients
- Developed AI-driven data extraction capabilities for alternative asset servicing and for NTRS's Front Office Solutions platform; partnered with Accelex

- Called out by Microsoft as an early adopter of Microsoft Copilot. 'We can actually use all the tools that we've bought from Microsoft to really automate that, look into our internal infrastructure and data, and serve up the answers to the
clients directly. So, I just think it's going to be a fun few years as this gets implemented.'
- Using AI in Wealth Management to digitize complex trust documents to make trust advisors more efficient.
- In 2024 10K, NTRS disclosed that the firm uses "a variety of machine learning and artificial intelligence solutions to process transactional activity more efficiently and to mitigate risk."

- In June 2025, the CFO noted that AI is "providing a ton of productivity in terms of just hours spent on things that would require a lot of manual processes that are not required anymore." He emphasized that while they can't attach an actual
number to the impact yet, "the potential is absolutely enormous on the AI side."

- In Sept. 2025, the COO noted specific productivity gains from AI implementations, inclduing GitHub deployment (with ~31% of developers' time saved), Copilot usage (helping employees "work smarter"), and quality control checks. The COO
characterized their AI journey as being in the "early innings."
US Bancorp
- The firm's U.S. Bank Commercial Rewards Card division, which was built off of the acquisition of TravelBank, utilizes AI to remove physical doumenting and manual processes in reporting.
- Introduced the Smart Assistant bot in its mobile app in 2020
- Launched an AI-powered savings tool for customers in 2021

- In 2023, the then-CEO commented, "Well, there are a number of use cases that we're working on in terms of customer service, customer interaction, next best action, a lot of things like that. So I would say, it's an active process across many

different areas of the bank and it impacts actually every single business line in one way, shape or form, as in addition to the operations and back room." He also believes timing of impacts is more of a 2-3 year story versus more near-term;

- In 2024, CEO commented that expense efficiences are 'sooner' than a 3-5 year story, with impacts in areas such as fraud prevention, customer service, call centers, contact centers and the ability to really solve the customer's problem
without having to have a call being made.
-Established a center of excellence with AI in the company and believe there's a step function with Gen AI occurring in the industry.
-AI/Machine Learning (ML) initiatives are listed among 'strategic digital investments' in the 2Q25 earnings presentaiton.
Wells Fargo
- Fargo is the firm's new AI-powered virtual assistant, recently went live on its mobile app for all consumer customers

- Customer Engagement Engine (CEE) is an internal tool for employees that relies on modeling and adaptive machine learning to recognize customer behavior in real-time conversations and offer tailored service-related messaging

- Vantage is the firm's new enhanced digital experience for commercial and corporate clients. This uses AI and machine learning to provide a tailored and intuitive platform based on clients' specific needs
- The firm has partnered with Microsoft Cloud, which allows WFC to utilize its AI capabilities

- 'The new opportunity that exists with Gen AI is where AI creates something based upon whether it's public data or our own data in terms of things that haven't existed. We are most focused in the shorter-term on things that can drive
efficiency [e.g. call centers], but it also contributes to just quality of the experience for our customers.'
- In February 2025, Wells cited "dozens and dozens of different use cases that are being piloted in some form across the company."

- In May 2025, the CEO described the AI opportunity as "transformative" while acknowledging they were "at the very beginning of figuring out how to get all of the right benefits inside of companies like ours."
- In June 2025, Wells noted development of "a whole set of use cases" focused specifically on driving efficiency, such as live piloting for call centers.

- In July 2025, Wells Freported that some early AI use cases were "starting to mature a little bit" and "starting to see some of the benefit you thought you'd see in terms of efficiency," though it was still "super, super early."
